---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import SectionLabel from '../../components/SectionLabel.astro';
---

<Base
  title="CalmAir Privacy Policy"
  description="CalmAir's privacy policy: the app collects no data, stores everything on your device, and makes exactly one narrow, optional network request to name your flight's departure and arrival cities."
>
  <section>
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-page px-8 py-section">
      <SectionLabel label="calmair · privacy policy" />
      <h1 class="mt-6 text-page-h1 text-text-primary max-w-prose">
        CalmAir collects nothing.
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-6 text-card-body text-text-secondary max-w-prose">
        Last updated: July 2026
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="mx-auto max-w-page px-8 section-divider"></div>

  <section>
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-page px-8 py-section max-w-prose space-y-8">
      <div>
        <h2 class="mono-label">Data collection</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-card-body text-text-secondary">
          CalmAir doesn't collect your data - nothing you generate in the app is ever sent to us
          or stored anywhere but your own device. There are no accounts, no sign-in, no analytics
          SDKs, and no advertising identifiers. Every reading the app produces - motion data,
          barometer data, location, flight history, your appearance preferences - is generated
          and stored entirely on your device. The one exception is described below under
          "Location", and even there, nothing is ever sent to us; only Apple sees a coordinate,
          transiently, to look up a city name.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="mono-label">Sensors</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-card-body text-text-secondary">
          CalmAir uses your iPhone's motion sensor and barometer, with your permission, only
          while a flight session is active. This data is processed on-device to classify
          turbulence and estimate flight phase, then discarded or reduced to small per-minute
          summaries stored locally. Raw sensor data is never saved and never leaves your phone.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="mono-label">Location</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-card-body text-text-secondary">
          With your permission, CalmAir records your location during an active flight to draw the
          route you flew and to keep recording turbulence if you switch to another app - iOS
          otherwise pauses the app within seconds of it leaving the screen. Your route is stored
          only on your device, drawn as a simple line, never as a map, and never transmitted
          anywhere.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3 text-card-body text-text-secondary">
          The one narrow exception: when a flight starts and again when it ends, CalmAir may send
          that single coordinate to Apple's built-in geocoding service to look up a city name (so
          your history can read "Cape Town → London" instead of raw coordinates). This only
          happens if you have connectivity at that moment - inflight wifi at the gate, for
          example - and is silently skipped with no loss of function if you don't, which is the
          common case since most passengers fly in airplane mode. Apple handles that request under
          its own privacy policy; CalmAir never receives, stores, or sees anything back beyond the
          city name itself, and nothing else about your flight is ever sent anywhere.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3 text-card-body text-text-secondary">
          You can decline location access entirely and CalmAir still works exactly the same for
          turbulence measurement - you'll just lose the flight-path drawing, the city labels, and
          the ability to keep recording if you switch apps mid-flight.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="mono-label">Storage</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-card-body text-text-secondary">
          Flight history, route data, settings, and purchase status are stored locally on your
          device using standard iOS storage (including the Keychain for purchase status).
          Deleting the app deletes this data. There is no cloud backup, no server, and no way for
          anyone - including the developer - to access it remotely.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="mono-label">Purchases</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-card-body text-text-secondary">
          CalmAir's lifetime unlock is processed entirely through Apple's In-App Purchase system.
          Payment details are handled by Apple and never seen by CalmAir or its developer.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="mono-label">Children</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-card-body text-text-secondary">
          CalmAir does not knowingly collect information from anyone, including children, because
          it does not collect information from anyone.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="mono-label">Changes to this policy</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-card-body text-text-secondary">
          If this policy ever changes, the update will be posted on this page with a new "last
          updated" date above.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="mono-label">Contact</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 text-card-body text-text-secondary">
          Questions about this policy: <a href="mailto:stewart@stewart-burton.com" class="text-accent hover:underline">stewart@stewart-burton.com</a>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
